Recommendations
We recommended, and the Management agreed, to ensure that the Municipal Accountant:
In coordination with the Municipal Treasurer:
Collect the long outstanding receivables particularly the accounts with available reference documents by sending demand letters letter per account per Accountable Officer to be issued three times every two weeks;
Exhaust all remedies to collect and properly document efforts made such as withholding of salaries, legal remedies and etc.; and
Locate all related documents pertaining to the long outstanding receivables in order to establish their existence and validity;
Develop an accounting estimate for impairment of receivables based on the management’s knowledge and experience on the settlement of its receivables taking into account the age and collectability of the balances, identified bad accounts eligible for write-off and other historical data such as settlement/liquidation and collection experience;
Assess at the end of each year or each reporting date whether there is evidence that the receivable accounts are impaired;
Support the assessment, if possible, with evidence enumerated in paragraph 8.3 of COA Circular No. 2016-005;
Calculate the allowance for impairment in accordance with the IPSAS and recognize the computed allowance in the books to reflect the net realizable value of the receivable accounts in the Financial Statements; and
Submit to the LCE the recommended list of eligible accounts for write-off.
We also recommended and Management agreed to:
File a request for the write-off of dormant accounts in accordance with the guidelines and procedures prescribed in COA Circular No. 2016-005, if warranted, without prejudice to the possible collection of accounts previously written off; and
Develop policies and guidelines outlining the methods and strategies to improve the collection and settlement of past due accounts and thereafter ensure strict adherence thereto to cleanse the books for the fair presentation of receivable accounts in the FS;

Recommendations
We recommended, and the Management agreed, through the Municipal Engineer, that:
At the beginning of each year, provide the Office of the Auditor with a comprehensive inventory of all active PPAs as well as those that are scheduled for implementation throughout the year;
Submit to COA the monthly monitoring report on the implementation of the PPAs using the template prescribed in the above-mentioned circular;
Upload and post the monthly monitoring report on the LGU’s website or LGU’s bulletin boards as part of its Transparency Seal; and
At every project site, the appropriate project signboards and/or public notices be installed to apprise the public of project details.

We reiterated our previous recommendation that the Local Chief Executive: 

a. designates an employee who is holding a regular plantilla position or employs a  General Services Officer under the direct supervision of the Municipal Treasurer who will take charge of the conduct of physical inventory of PPE items; 

b. creates Inventory committee with the composition stated above to facilitate the physical count and/or verification of all PPE of the Municipality; and prepare and submit the result of the factual verification through RPCPPE to the audit team.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:
to conduct a risk assessment; 
to identify critical processes and functions; 
to determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation; 
to conduct risk analysis and impact analysis; 
to formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to mitigate the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and
to submit a plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.
We also recommended that Management improve their monitoring of operational requirements like the submission of PSCP.

Require the Municipal Accountant to reclassify the unserviceable assets to Other Assets account in the books of the municipality;

Require the Disposal/Inventory Committee to dispose immediately the damaged/unserviceable assets;

Require the Municipal Accountant to effect adjustments in the books based on the disposed properties.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant maintain a separate special account in the General Fund for loans wherein the receipts and expenditures thereof are recorded so that accurate and separate information on the status of loans is readily available for decision-making purposes; 
and
Observed timely payments of its loan amortization and interests due to avoid the incurrence of penalties on the failure of such.

We recommended the following:

1. The Municipal Assessor to provide a copy of an updated Assessment Roll to the Municipal Treasurer pursuant to Article 339 of the IRR of RA No. 7160 which states that the Municipal Assessor shall submit an assessment roll containing a list of all persons whose real properties have been newly assessed and the values of such properties to the Municipal Treasurer concerned on or before the 31st day of December each year;

2. The Municipal Treasurer to update the RPT Account Register/ Taxpayer’s index card based on the Assessment Roll and furnish the Municipal Accountant a duly certified list showing the names of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year;

3. The Municipal Accountant to draw a JEV to record the debit to RPT/SET Receivables and credit to Deferred RPT/ SET Income based on the certified list of due and collectible RPT for the year submitted by the Municipal Treasurer; and

4. The Municipal Accountant to reconcile recordings involving RPT/ SET transactions and make necessary correcting/ adjusting entries.

Recommendations
We recommended and management agreed that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to:
Exert extra effort to cause the immediate liquidation of cash advances with special attention to those long over-due advances by sending demand letters if appropriate, follow-up communications to all concerned personnel, and/or reclassification to appropriate due from accounts;
Closely monitor cash advances and prevent granting another similar cash advances;
Request for write-off supported with proper documents, if appropriate; and
Strengthen the internal control on the grant and liquidation of cash advances, including the constant re-awareness and reminders to the Municipality’s officials and employees on the proper, complete and timely liquidation.

